    "industrial_process_notes": "Originally developed before WWII in Germany by chemist Walter Bock in 1929; during WWII the U.S. Synthetic Rubber Program produced Government Rubber-Styrene (GR-S) at scale to replace inaccessible Southeast Asian natural rubber. Two production routes: emulsion polymerization (E-SBR, historically more widely used) and solution polymerization (S-SBR, growing share in tire applications). ~5.4 million tonnes processed worldwide in 2012.",
